column3: "I chose D6 (I think I made a mistake and entered D1 instead of D6) because it will force circle to play at a3 to stop the win. Afterwards X can play at C4 to prevent Circle from creating a winning situation. Beyond that I wasn't able to fully figure it out. I felt that the only way to prevent circle from winning was to pick either D6 or a3 to force them to play at a specific spot."
"I played out the game through trial and error. I tried finding ways that I could set it up so that I would eventually have 2 ways to win."
"I chose a spot closer to the other x's."

"X must place in d4 on the first move no matter what or he will lose. If X places anywhere else, O can place in d4 and will win on turn 2 no matter what. So the only way X has a chance to win is to place in d4 first."
"i looked at the board to see where 4 xs would fit with an extra square available"
"The circle was one move away from making a line of 3 with both endings open and win the next move, so I had to constantly force it to block my 4th X in line"
"I wanted to cut off the o so it had less of a chance to strategize then I did "
"I tried to force them to have to block runs of 3 until they couldn't anymore"

"Basically O has position they can play and force a win in 2 turns.  X either has to fill that position or force O to play in other positions else lose immediately.  With the state of the board, X can play 4-5 turns where they force 0 to play defensively else they lose immediately.  Then after those 4-5 plays x can put itself in the position to where it's impossible to lose ( i think, hope i didn't make an oversight)."
"I tried to find a move that would present multiple threats that O would have to be forced to respond to or lose"
"I tried to put x in a place where it can win no matter what o does. "
"I was trying to force each of O's next moves and at the same time add to the number of options I had to improve my position."

"I looked just one move ahead. Really I needed to put the x's on the board in order to visualize.\nI looked to put my x close to where I already had established a group of x's, like a critical mass. Then I could build around that cluster."
"I don't know.  I just tried various moves until I found one that worked."
"I looked at the board and determined which move would result in the most possible in a row situations for x "
"I tried to make it so there was a win-win on both ends for x"
"Not much of a strategy, I just went with my gut and tried to analyze what O Would do, but still, X ended up winning."
"I just tried to imagine playing the game really, then I input the circle moves in logical places to check."
"Starting with this square seems to end up giving me multiple options to win"
"By attempting to find which solution would create the final outcome of 3 x's in a row with space on either side."
"I wanted to have a chance of winning diagonally while preventing O from winning with 4 in a row sideways. "
"I basically played against myself until I felt I couldn't beat x\n"
"Was the most inconspicuous placement and would leave many win options available for x while o would have to attempt to block several"
"It was the move that provided the most opportunities for a win after in a 5 move win"

"I attempted to try out different first move strategies for X and then compared them to o's likely responses. Since o was threatening in two different locations a logical first step for X would have to be to take one of those moves away so it narrowed down what X could do to both block O and try to advance to win themselves considerable to just two to three different locations I then played around with the few different locations I had identified to see what seemed best."
"I focused on a way to make them constantly have to try and stop me, while I still made progress to win. That seemed like the way to win and I think it worked. "
"I started by marking a spot where x could win up or down depending on where o played."
"First I noticed that O has several opportunities to set up unblocked 3-row so I looked for ways to force O's moves while building up the ability to set up my own 3-row."

"find the spot that give X multiple paths to win no matter which spot O tries to block\nin one more move. it helped that the instructions say X can win\nbecause with just a brief introduction, I might not be sure that would be possible"
"I tried to think as both players would and pick the best moves. "
"I tried to really put myself in the shoes of player O. I tried many different spots until I found the right move."
"I placed an X in 2 consecutive spots where I would have more than 1 chance of winning."
"I tried to make it to where no matter what I did X would win"
"I wanted to be sure to block 0"
"The way that it played x also blocked o from a 4 of a kind but the way it worked x would have 2 option for a 4 of a kind played the way I did."
"Placing an X there would give me two winning areas, diagonal and horizontal, so they'd have to block one and I could work on the other."
"I made sure to force the O player to have to defend every move or else X wins.  This allows me to know what O will do and work a new long term strategy."
"I looked at the board and assigned a value to each square, and then placed the mark for each round on the square with the highest score in my weighting system."
"I looked to see what would be the best first play for x. Then I just tried to play every way best for O. If I couldn't block my best attempt with O, I was good."
"I tried to find a situation where no matter what option my opponent chose I still had an opening to win. I did that by trial and error. I tested many different options."
"Made sure I had two possible moves to win by enticing o to move to a certain square."
"using the strategy shown in the example before where the player places their mark on two squares, i chose a spot where x would not only have doubles going in one direction, but in two directions. "
"Just tried placing different marks on the board until I found something that worked"
